ale and female authors portray women, the treatment of sexuality in Scottish writing, the construction of Scottish masculinity and its relation to class and homophobia. Covering modern fiction and theatre, poetry, film and television, it is a provocative reassessment of the gender and culture of a 'stateless nation'.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / LGBT.2bisacsh1 aCalder, Jenni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElphinstone, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonda, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJack, R. D. S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorgan, Edwin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchoene, Berthold, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScullion, Adrienne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhyte, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z97831107804750 cprintz978074860619140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147447358340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474473583423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474473583/original  a978-3-11-078047-5  Edinburgh University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK